Jared - Per our call on Friday, my recommendation is to get the lawyers on the phone this week to try and advance
the ball. My understanding from our counsel is that your counsel is only available at 4:30pm ET today. Given the
pending deadlines, and the fact that your counsel is unavailable to speak with us, we believe your interests would
be best served by getting new counsel who can engage quickly. In terms of your other points:

First, although you state that you are not looking to back out of any contract with CardConnect, your counter-claim and
your request for a declaratory judgment is premised on there being no contract. This is a matter of fact and record, not
opinion.

Second, you claim that you were not looking to use CardConnect's intellectual property when you asked for it and
sought to buy it. That argument is not credible. I appreciate the points I expect you are going to make, but they are
the type of arguments that lawyers make, after the fact, but the actual emails tell the story. You asked to buy
CardConnect's IP and said that what you were building would not compete with CardConnect, and then said the
opposite a few months later. These are the facts.
On your claim that you provided notice of termination, our contract, which you acknowledge, is clear that notice of
termination must be given no later than ninety (90) days prior to the end of the then-current term, in writing. Your
position that the MPSA can be terminated at the time of your choosing is not supported by the contract.

With respect to your final point, CardConnect has spent approximately 2 years supporting the commercial launch of
your product, and have paid you a lot of money. Your claim that CardConnect needs to continue to pay you, while
at the same time you are going to compete with CardConnect and circumvent your obligations to us is not reasonable.

I understand we have two very different views on this matter. The purpose of my call was to try and resolve the
business issues.

Please ask your counsel to reach out to ours to discuss these issues further.

prop info. That is why we filed the suit. While I understand that your position is different, and that you expect the
contract to continue, you can't unilaterally terminate the deal because paying you on active accounts is too
expensive, or as you said to me, 'we are the losers on the deal'. I did not say I pay $300 million to get out of it. I

we originally asked, and I did not know how to value that, but prob in the $200 to $300 million range depending on
the number of merchants. You said that sounded optimistic to you.

We should prob focus on getting the lawyers to discuss this week.
